description.plain:
The lo-fi bedroom track “All You Gotta Be When You’re 23 Is Yourself” takes its name from a quote from the 1994 film Reality Bites. In the film, the main character tries to figure out her next steps after graduating college. The song centers on themes from the movie, including growing up and finding yourself in the “real world.”

The soft-spoken song served as the band’s breakout single and, consequently, featured on both the moving songs EP and debut album talking quietly of anything with you.

annotations:
Cause all you gotta be when you’re 23
 Is yourself

When your 23, you really start to do things on your own. you’ve been through all of it, elementary school, middle school, high school, and now you’ve just finished college. What are you gonna do with your life? what are you gonna be?  Katie Bennet reminds us that its okay to take things slow and not feel pressured to “Do something.” you’re only 23, all you have to be is yourself.

description.plain: “For You” is a dedication-style love song that peruses of the various things the narrator would do for the protagonist when they fall in love. It describes the pure but child-like adoration during the experience of love, and manages to express the emotion with comic relief, crooning, and doughnuts.

writer_artists.name: Ian Stewart (free cake for every creature)

annotations: Like a bottle out to sea
This line uses “a bottle out at sea” as a metaphor for their love; the ocean has infinite possibilities and is immeasurable and permanent.
For you i’d steal a fifty cent machine

Another line reinforcing the child-like influence of love. ‘Fifty cent machines’ (or 20p machines, which are more common in the UK) are often placed outside arcades or family leisure areas, and filled will brightly coloured, encapsulated small toys or candy than can be obtained by inserting the coin required into the machine.

You are the brownie to my tv dinner
 But i don’t wanna save you for later

Katie puts a spin on the cliché of referring to someone as “the yin to their yang” and makes this line simultaneously more relatable and memory-inciting with a reference to TV dinners, which are symbolic of a childhood memory.

The narrator referring to the protagonist as the brownie in the meal signifies that they are a treat to look forward to, so much so that impatience grows when they are away.
